    "text": "CAPE TOWN (Reuters) - South Africa’s drought-stricken city of Cape Town has pushed back its estimate for “Day Zero,” when residents will have to start queuing for water, to May 11 from April 16, authorities said on Monday, citing a decline in agricultural water usage.\nSlideshow (2 Images) “Capetonians must continue reducing consumption if we are to avoid Day Zero,” Cape Town’s executive deputy major, Alderman Ian Neilson, was Quote: d as saying.\nNeilson added: “All Capetonians must therefore continue to use no more than 50 liters per person per day to help stretch our dwindling supplies.”\nReporting by Wendell Roelf; Writing by Alexander Winning; Editing by James Macharia\n ",
